{"key":"post-9391020","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9391020</id>\n<content>I recommend around a teaspoon of hydrated lime per cup of peat.&amp;nbsp; That will leave you around 8.5 for a day or two, when it settles down to around 7.5 or so.&amp;nbsp; I suspect your pH meter isn't calibrated, especially if you used gypsum at ten percent of the volume of peat.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You might try repeating the test after calibrating your meter in pH 7 solution.&amp;nbsp; Be sure to filter the material back out of the water and test only water, especially if you are using a bulb type pH meter.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You might also check your label against the picture below.&amp;nbsp; When using hydrated lime, it's important to use &lt;i&gt;horticultura&lt;/i&gt;l hydrated lime, not the type intended for masonry.&lt;br /&gt;RR&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/06-29/352394956-hydrated_lime_label.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/06-29/352394956-thumb_hydrated_lime_label.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/032303-8/89949-lime1.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/032303-8/89949-thumb_lime1.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9391053</next>\n<prev>9391002</prev>\n<first>9391002</first>\n<last>9393119</last>\n<when>1228753532</when>\n<utime>12/08/08 06:25 PM</utime>\n</post>"}